@article{Dupont2007,
   abstract = {Effect of Short Recovery Intensities on the Performance during Two Wingate Tests. Med. Sci. Sports Exerc., Vol. 39, No. 7, pp. 1170–1176, 2007. Purpose: To assess the effects of the intensity of short recoveries on performance by a Wingate test and on the deoxyhemoglobin variations. Methods: Twelve male subjects performed a graded test and three sessions of repeated all-out tests with different recovery natures. The repeated all-out tests included two sprints: a 15-s Wingate test followed by a 30-s Wingate test. The recovery between the two was 15 s in duration and was either passive, active at 20\{\%\} of maximal aerobic power, or active at 40\{\%\} of maximal aerobic power. Changes in deoxyhemoglobin were measured using by the near-infrared spectroscopy technique. Results: Mean power (517 T 26 W) and peak power (1085 T 153 W) of the 30-s Wingate test performed after passive recovery were significantly higher (P G 0.05) than mean power and peak power performed after active recovery at 20\{\%\} (484 T 30 and 973 T 112 W, respectively) and 40\{\%\} of maximal aerobic power (492 T 35 and 928 T 116 W, respectively). Deoxyhemoglobin variations were significantly higher (P G 0.05) during the passive recovery (12.8 T 5.3 KM) than during the active recovery conditions at 20\{\%\} (4.3 T 2.6 KM) and 40\{\%\} of maximal aerobic power (3.9 T 2.6 KM). Conclusion: These results demonstrate that when two Wingate tests are performed almost successively but with a short recovery between the two, passive recovery is more appropriate than active recovery to restore the performance level. Key},
