   abstract = {The majority of in vivo applications of near-infrared spectroscopic (NIRS) monitoring use continuous wave instruments that require a ﬁberoptic cable connection between the subject and the instrument during monitoring. In studies of muscle physiology where subjects are exercising, and particularly in those who are engaged in sports activity, a wireless instrument with telemetric capacity provides obvious advantages. Having access to reliable telemetric NIRS technology will also increase the practicality and scope of this biomedical monitoring technique in clinical settings.},
